financed some of the world's best-known and greatest artwork. The essays explore the issue of identity and its maintenance, of carving a permanent spot for a family name in a rapidly changing atmosphere.Although these studies depart from art patronage, they uncover how the popes, cardinals, dukes, and signore of the della Rovere family constituted their identity. Originally a nouveau-riche creation of papal nepotism, the della Rovere first populated the ranks of cardinals under the powerful popes Sixtus IV and Julius II. Within the framework of later papal relations, the family negotiated its position within the economy of Italian nobles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt, RenaissancezItaly. 0aNobilityzItalyxHistoryy15th century. 0aNobilityzItalyxHistoryy16th century. 0aPapacyxHistoryy1447-1565. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh1 aBauman, Lisa Passaglia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlondin, Jill Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlume, Andrew C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConelli, Maria Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Henry Dietrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontana, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLingo, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Caroline P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerstegen, Ian F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVerstegen, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014